AGI - "Si vis pacem, para bellum", the Latins said. "If you want peace, prepare war." And therefore, in Capri, the Foreign Ministers of the Great of the Earth insist on giving new weapons to Ukraine, especially for air defense, because otherwise Kiev risks being defeated and does not convince the Kremlin to open negotiations. "If Kiev loses, Putin does not sit at the table of peace," said Foreign Minister, Antonio Tajani, opening up the work of the meeting under the Italian presidency. "Helping Ukraine means working for peace. Because only if there is balance in the field," Putin will sit at a negotiating table.
&nbsp;
In Capri, the Ukrainian Foreign Minister, Dmytro Kuleba, repeated the demands of Kiev, indeed said that the air defense is "a matter of life or death". Ukraine believes that the Allies should have with Ukraine the same attitude had with Israel, when France, the USA and the Gb last weekend intercepted Iranian missiles. And before the heads of U.S. diplomats, Canada, Japan, France, Great Britain and Germany, as well as the EU, Kuleba has clarified the demands: "The priority is the American Patriots and the Samp/T, the French-Italian defense system," "the only ones capable of intercepting Russian ballistic missiles." "You are considering what you can give and what availability there is," said Tajani. "Italy has no Patriot so it is not a question that concerns Italy."
&nbsp;
To relaunch the appeal of Kuleba thought of NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg: Member States must offer Ukrainian resistance air defense systems (as Germany has just done with a Patriot system) or alternatively financial support because "every day of delay costs human lives and other damage caused by the Russian invasion". In this sense, he recalled that the Netherlands just confirmed a package of 4 billion euros of additional military aid and Denmark announced new commitments; and he defined "an encouraging signal" Washington's decision, after months of stall, to discuss the approval (and probably vote on Saturday) the financial aid package for 61 billion dollars, with the commitment of American President Joe Biden to ratify them immediately. In its view, speeding up aid to Ukraine is "urgent" because "every day of delay costs dead and damage" caused by Russia pressing on defensive lines.
&nbsp;
"That's why we have to do more and that's why we are here," Stoltenberg insisted, which tomorrow will see the Ukrainian president, Volodymyr Zelensky, in video connection to the NATO-Ukraine Council. The 'free way' to the US Congress would actually be an encouraging sign for peace, Tajani echoed it. In the meeting with Kuleba, the US Secretary of State, Antony Blinken, insisted on the " urgency" that the House of Representatives, which is dominated by the republican opposition, approve the new package of aid. "At this moment, it is urgent that all the friends and supporters of Ukraine make the most effort to continue to provide Kiev with what it needs to defend itself."
&nbsp;
Ukrainian prime minister Denys Shmyhal, today has even evoked the risk of "The Third World War": "We need this money yesterday... Not tomorrow, not today." The head of EU diplomacy, Josep Borrell, told European countries that it is necessary to "support Ukraine faster and better" because Russia continues to hit cities and electrical infrastructure and the country risks black-out: "We have the Patriots, we have the antimissile systems cannot remain in the warehouses"; and European countries "can not rely only on the United States, but must assume their responsibilities.

