AGI - "The G7 countries have renewed full, shared and convinced support to Ukraine, renewing confidence in the country that will be able to overcome the difficulties". This was said by the Minister of Economy Giancarlo Giorgetti, who yesterday presided over the session of the interministerial G7 in Washington, where the gothha of world finance met. With him, in the Italian delegation, there was the governor of Bankitalia Fabio Panetta. During the summit, the minister opened a brief discussion on Ukraine, in the presence of Ukrainian Minister Sergii Marcenko. “We encourage Fmi, the World Bank and all other relevant financial institutions – said the minister – to continue supporting Ukraine and its macroeconomic stability.”
&nbsp;
Giorgetti invited Marcenko to the financial G7 in Stresa from 23 to 25 May. At the heart of the meeting also the reforms of the multilateral development banks and updates of the IMS and the health and finance agenda. On the issue of international taxation Giorgetti stressed the importance of continuing the work already done in the G7 G20 in São Paulo to achieve the goal of signing to the Convention by the end of June of this year. “It is important to maintain a high degree of coordination between the G7 - said &nbsp; the minister - especially if the discussion advances along lines that are not fully shared.” At closed doors, the G7 discussed the Russian assets frozen after the Russian invasion of Ukraine, a subject that sees the Italian presidency taking “a very delicate task”, concluded Giorgetti.
