AGI - Laws should be changed so as to ensure that slap a child is not considered acceptable under any circumstances. The Royal College of Pediatrics and Child Health, or Rcpch, in the UK. The current law in England and Northern Ireland has created gray areas, which means that sometimes there is a defense against physical punishment. Wales made any kind of bodily punishment illegal, including slaps, blows and shocks, in March 2022, while Scotland had already introduced a similar ban in November 2020. Rcpch now calls for this policy to be adopted throughout the United Kingdom, claiming that the amendments to eliminate the defence of "reasonable cleansing" by the Children Act 2004 for England and the Law Reform Order 2006 for Northern Ireland have long been "waited". His report on the subject states that, in view of political elections, it is time for all political parties to "take significant commitments on this important issue of children's rights". According to the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health, laws in force in England and Northern Ireland have created gaps, which sometimes allow to defend physical punishment. The report warns that children who suffer physical punishment have a nearly triple probability of developing a worse mental health and a more than double chance of suffering serious physical aggression and abuse. Physical punishment also increases the likelihood of behavioral problems during childhood, poorer relationships with parents and family and cases of aggression later in life.
&nbsp;
At international level, 65 states have completely banned physical punishment on children and 27 others have committed to reforming their laws to reach a complete legal ban. But, in England and Northern Ireland, adults continue to be more protected than children. "The laws on physical punishment, in their present form, are unjust and dangerously vague," said Andrew Rowland, pediatrician consultant and Rcpch's head for child protection. "They grow a shadow zone where some forms of physical punishment may be lawful and others may not," Rowland continued. "As a pediatrician working in child protection services, I am regularly faced with situations where physical punishments have been used against a child. The vague nature of the laws makes it extremely difficult to talk to families about the rules on the physical punishment of children, making it so difficult to talk about the interest of their children."
&nbsp;
"This lack of legislative clarity can even add another level of complexity when trying to identify cases of child abuse," said Rowland. "The view of society on punishment has changed over time, with two out of three adults who now agree that physical punishment on children is unacceptable.
&nbsp;
The laws on physical punishment, in their present form, are unjust and dangerously vague," said Rowland. "There must not be shadowy areas when it comes to safeguarding children." "The change of laws in England and Northern Ireland will give us absolute clarity and will ensure that there are no cases where it is acceptable or lawful to beat a child," said Rowland. "The science on the physical punishment of children is now consolidated," said Bess Herbert, an advocacy expert in the international organization End Corporal Punishment. "Centinaia of studies found that they are associated with a wide range of negative outcomes," Herbert said. "I hope that England and Northern Ireland will soon join the growing number of countries that have taken this fundamental step to protect children, defend their rights and support healthy and positive growth of children." "The requests for amendments to the law are motivated by ideology, not clinical evidence and elected representatives must reject them," said Simon Calvert, of the Be Reasonable Campaign. "The current law strongly prohibits all forms of violence against children, while protecting parents from criminal actions for innocent and harmless decisions of parents," said Calvert.
&nbsp;
"The exception of reasonable punishment is, by definition, limited to the actions which the court considers reasonable." "Children in England and Northern Ireland continue to be exposed to a legal loophole that can undermine their fundamental right to protection with the excuse of reasonable punishment," warned Joanna Barrett, NPCC. "As this timely report of Rcpch's childhood health experts shows, beating a child can have harmful and lasting consequences. We know from Childline that physical punishment can impact the child's mental and emotional health and damage the relationship between parents and children. That is why we ask the political leaders of England and Northern Ireland to commit themselves to ending physical punishment on children, as the other countries of the United Kingdom have successfully done." &nbsp;

